South Korea  will expand monitoring
of overseas investment trends in the country and capital
outflows amid rising financial market volitility caused by the
European fiscal crisis, the Financial Supervisory Service said.  The regulator will review the soundness of local banksâ€™
foreign-currency assets, encourage lenders to diversify funding
sources and to borrow funds with long-term maturity, FSS
Governor Kwon Hyouk Se told lawmakers today in  Seoul , according
to an e-mailed copy of his speech.  To contact the reporter on this story:
